Here's how to implement all three pieces:

**1 & 2. Intercept back navigation with a confirmation dialog**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` in your page:

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (!_hasUnsavedChanges)
            return base.OnBackButtonPressed();

        // Fire-and-forget since the override is synchronous
        Dispatcher.Dispatch(async () =>
        {
            bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (leave)
                await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
        });

        return true; // cancel the default navigation
    }
}
```

> **Note:** `OnBackButtonPressed` only fires for the **hardware/OS back button** (Android). It does *not* fire when the user taps Shell's navigation-bar back arrow.

**3. Replace the Shell back arrow with a custom "Cancel" button**

To intercept the **nav-bar** back button, hide it and add your own toolbar item:

```xml
<ContentPage
    xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
    x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage"
    Shell.BackButtonBehavior="{x:Null}">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior
            TextOverride="Cancel"
            Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

Then in your view model (or code-behind):

```csharp
public ICommand BackCommand { get; }

public EditProductPageViewModel()
{
    BackCommand = new AsyncRelayCommand(OnBackRequested);
}

private async Task OnBackRequested()
{
    if (!HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
        return;
    }

    bool leave = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
        "Unsaved Changes",
        "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
        "Discard", "Stay");

    if (leave)
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

**Key points:**
- `BackButtonBehavior.Command` replaces the nav-bar arrow tap — your command runs instead of default navigation.
- `OnBackButtonPressed` handles the Android hardware back button separately.
- Both paths share the same confirmation logic, so extract it into a helper if you want to stay DRY.
